{
  "text": "The different motor combinations which allow controlled jinger movement. Equations (4) show that the displacements of the finger motors with zero slacks are only function of the proximal two joints (MCP, PIP), which means that the free moving model effectively functions as a bi-articular chain. In this chain, five motors are present, while for full control mathematically three suffice [CITATION_1] . Therefore, two motors will be mathematically redundant. In the normal finger the redundancies are with the flexors (P and S), and the intrinsics (L and I). The conditions for flexor redundancy were investigated in [CITATION_2] . The redundancy of the intrinsics is investigated further. These redundancies are expressed in the control equation (4g), which defines the motor combinations which in the normal finger allow controlled finger movement. With the normal redundancy conditions satisfied, these motor combinations are:",
